{
  "doc_id": "43009",
  "text": "Although diarrhea is common in neonatal livestock, there are potentially many pathogens that may be involved apart from C. difficile, such as enterotoxigenic Escherichia coli, C. perfringens, Coccidia sp., Cryptosporidium sp., Giardia sp., and rotavirus, among others. In Australia , Europe, and North America [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , it is rare for other pathogens to be present with C. difficile in fecal samples, suggesting that C. difficile alone was associated with diarrhea. However, the importance of screening for other pathogens when undertaking C. difficile surveys should not be ignored.",
